  "prompt": "How do deaf people communicate?",
  "response": "Deaf individuals communicate using various methods, depending on their preferences, experiences, and the context of their interactions. Here are some common forms of communication used by deaf people:\n\n1. **Sign Language**: Many deaf individuals use sign languages, which are fully developed languages with their own grammar and lexicon. Examples include American Sign Language (ASL), British Sign Language (BSL), and others specific to different countries and regions. Sign languages utilize gestures, facial expressions, and body language to convey meaning.\n\n2. **Lip Reading**: Some deaf individuals rely on lip reading, which involves interpreting spoken language by visually observing the movements of the lips, facial expressions, and gestures. This skill can be challenging and is often used in conjunction with other communication methods.\n\n3. **Written Communication**: Deaf individuals may use written language to communicate, whether through texting, emailing, or using pen and paper. This method can be effective for conversations with hearing people who may not know sign language.\n\n4. **Cued Speech**: This system uses hand shapes and placements in conjunction with spoken language to clarify sounds. It is intended to assist deaf individuals in understanding spoken language better and is often used in educational settings.\n\n5. **Technology**: Many deaf individuals use technology to communicate, including video calls using sign language through applications like Skype or Zoom, text messaging, and captioning services for videos and live events.\n\n6. **Communication Aids**: Some deaf individuals use hearing devices, such as cochlear implants or hearing aids, to enhance their ability to hear and communicate verbally.\n\n7. **Body Language and Gestures**: Non-verbal cues, body language, and gestures play a significant role in communication among deaf individuals, whether they are using sign language or other forms of communication.\n\nUltimately, communication styles will vary greatly among deaf individuals, and many use a combination of these methods to interact effectively with others.",
